<F P=100> Vietnam </F>
<H3> <TI>   Radio on Economic Activities in Last 6 Months </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Radio on Economic Activities in Last 6 Months </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK2706140394 Hanoi Voice of Vietnam in English 1000 GMT 27 
Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2706140394 </F>
<F P=104>  Hanoi Voice of Vietnam </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] In the first six months of this year, Vietnam's 
economy has seen sound development. According to the Ministry 
of Trade, in the multisectoral economy, state commerce remains a 
key distributor of a number of essential items such as tin, 
cement, and petrol. This has helped balance supply and demand. 
  In the period under review, Vietnam's export turnover was 
1.6 
billion U.S. dollar, an increase of 27 percent against the same 
period last year, of which the turnover of rubber increased by 
28 percent, coffee 29 percent, tea 21 percent, and coal 24 
percent. 
  Meanwhile, Vietnam's import turnover in the last six months 
was recorded at 1.7 billion U.S. dollar. The main imports were 
those in service of production development and daily life such 
as petrol and pesticide. 
  Thanks to the production development, Vietnam has exported 
many items to foreign markets, including garment, crude oil, 
rice, maritime products, and tea. By now, Vietnam's Ministry of 
Trade has completed all necessary procedures to become an 
observer of GATT. It has signed trade agreements with Laos, 
Cambodia, and China and worked out plans for commercial 
promotion inside and outside of Vietnam. 

</TEXT>

