<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Council Sees Greater Reliance on Nuclear Energy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Council Sees Greater Reliance on Nuclear Energy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2406140194 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 21 Jun 
94 Evening Edition p 2 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2406140194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Advisory Committee for Energy (advisory body to 
the minister of international trade and industry) held a 
subcommittee meeting on demand and supply on 21 June to compile 
a long-term estimate on the demand and supply of energy up to 
the year 2010. 
  The estimate sees reliance on oil in 2010 to decline by 10.5 
percentage points to 47.7 percent. Annual rate of increase in 
demand will be held down to around 1 percent, 0.4 percent lower 
than the growth rate originally projected in 1990. The Ministry 
of International Trade and Industry [MITI] will implement its 
energy policy according to this estimate. 
  The long-term energy demand and supply estimate is compiled 
every two to four years to project future demand and supply. 
The present one is intended to be a numerical basis for 
implementing new policies, and will serve as a guideline for 
future government energy policy. 
  According to the projection, energy demand in 2010, 
converted 
into crude oil, will be 423 million kiloliters, representing an 
increase of 62 million kiloliters compared to the actual demand 
in FY 1992. While demand for industrial energy, or energy used 
in factories, will remain low, demand for energy from the 
nonindustrial sectors, such as households, and the 
transportation sector is expected to grow. 
  In terms of supply, reliance on oil and other mineral fuels 
will be reduced substantially to avert the greenhouse effect. 
Nuclear energy will be increased to become the number two 
primary energy source, while use of natural gas will also be 
expanded. The plan also calls for increasing new energy 
sources, such as solar energy and power generation using 
garbage, by 1.8 percent over that in 1992 to 3 percent of 
overall energy supply. As a result, it will be possible to hold 
down per capita emission of carbon dioxide in the year 2000 to 
the 1990 level. 
  Based on this estimate, the government plans to set targets 
for oil-substitute energy, which will be decided upon by a 
cabinet meeting in July. 
  MITI's Agency of Natural Resources and Energy is considering 
introducing the summer time system, as well as development of 
energy-saving technology, including electric cars and 
next-generation liquid crystal display equipment, to achieve 
these targets. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-30698 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas125__a94018" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-125-A </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  27 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   `East Asian Energy-Information Highway' Planned </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `East Asian Energy-Information Highway' Planned </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2806143294 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 27 Jun 
94 Evening Edition p 2 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2806143294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The National Land Agency [NLA] will start studying 
"East Asia Energy-Information Highway Plan," designed to connect 
Japan with East Asia region by placing pipelines. Investing 
Japan's technological and financial power in the project, the 
NLA aims to complete the project, which will establish a new 
industrial and communications base in cooperation with other 
Asian nations, around the year 2020. The NLA has worked out the 
plan in line with the National Land Development Council's 
recommendation that "it is necessary to work out a national land 
development plan that covers the Asia-Pacific region." The NLA 
plans to put the finishing touches on the project at a meeting 
of a research panel which will be established in June, with aim 
of incorporating the project in the next national land 
development plan. 
  The project is to establish energy and power supply lines 
and 
optical-fiber information and communications lines by placing 
huge pipelines between Japan and the East Asian region, 
including Russia, South Korea, and China. According the plan, 
the pipelines, starting in Siberia, will run through to Japan 
via Sakhalin and will reach China via the Korean Peninsula. In 
addition to these pipelines, the NLA plans to place transport 
pipelines for raw materials. 
  With the establishment of pipelines, it will be easy for 
Japan to obtain resources from Asian nations, and its supply of 
energy and raw materials will also be stabilized. The project, 
which includes the placement of high-speed, mass-storage 
communications lines, will also help promote and improve the 
international exchange of information. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-30699 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas125__a94019" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-125-A </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  17 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Taiwan Imposes Dumping Tariffs on Polypropylene </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Taiwan Imposes Dumping Tariffs on Polypropylene </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   942A0352B Tokyo NIKKEI SANGYO SHIMBUN in Japanese 17 Jun 94 
p 13--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> 942A0352B </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIKKEI SANGYO SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
CSO 

  [Text] The Petrochemical Industry Association (Chairman 
Hajime Murata) revealed on 16 June that Taiwan has levied an 
antidumping tariff on polypropylene (PP) resin made by Japan and 
South Korea. According to the association, a maximum 68.71 
percent tariff has been superimposed on the regular import 
tariff (2.5 percent) for Japanese products. It is the first time 
that Japanese resin has become the target of an antidumping 
tariff. 
  In the fall of 1992, a complaint was received from a 
Taiwanese PP manufacturer, Taiwan Polypropylene (Taipei), that 
it suffered a disadvantage because both Japanese and South 
Korean manufacturers imported PP at an unreasonably low price, 
and Taiwan authorities carried out an investigation starting in 
June 1993. While Japanese manufacturers submitted data, they 
counterargued in a public hearing that "they are importing 
product items that cannot be manufactured in Taiwan," but it was 
not accepted. 
  The subject of the tariff is the PP homopolymer type used 
mainly for sundries. An antidumping tariff of 5.16 to 68.71 
percent for each manufacturer has been imposed according to the 
difference between domestic shipment price in Japan and export 
price to Taiwan. The same tariffs will be applied even in cases 
where manufacturers who have not previously exported to Taiwan 
newly export. 
  The amount of raw material propylene production is slight in 
Taiwan, the amount of PP production is about 220,000 tons 
(1993), and they depend on imports for about the same amount 
(little over 190,000 tons, 1993). Exports from Japan were 45,000 
tons of this (1993). 
  Regarding the effect of the antidumping tariff, the 
Petrochemical Industry Association explains that, "since 
necessary items will probably be imported in the future also, it 
will not be zero. Since the export amount for each individual 
manufacturer is small, it will not be a problem." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-30700 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas125__a94020" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-125-A </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  17 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ethylene Imports Increase </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ethylene Imports Increase </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   942A0352C Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 17 Jun 94 p 
29--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> 942A0352C </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
CSO 

  [Text] The import of ethylene, a basic petrochemical raw 
material, is rapidly increasing. The ethylene plants of various 
petrochemical companies have a surplus over about 20 percent, 
but it is due to manufacturers one after the other suspending 
plant operations with the objective of production adjustment and 
there conversely becoming a sense of product shortage. 
Previously, other companies in the industry accommodated each 
other on shortages, but a big deficit on synthetic resins has 
affected various companies and recently they have begun to be 
reluctant to accommodate at cheap prices, spurring an increase 
in imports. 
  Imports began to increase in April this year. According to 
trade statistics, the amount of imports for April was 11,500 
tons (no record of imports for the same month of the previous 
year). It was double that of March, and nearly half of the 
amount of 1993 imports (24,834 tons) was achieved within the one 
month of April. 
  The importer for the most part has been South Korea. All 
ethylene manufacturers such as Showa Denko, Mitsui 
Petrochemical, Maruzen Petrochemical, and Tonen Chemical, are 
buying. The price of South Korean ethylene is about 40 to 45 yen 
per kilo. 
  While some say that the reason for imports is that "There is 
a temporary shortage of ethylene due to suspending operations 
for regularly scheduled plant repairs" (Maruzen Petrochemical), 
there also are manufacturers who point out that, "Imports can be 
bought cheaper than buying domestic" (Showa Denko). 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-30701 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas125__a94021" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-125-A </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  17 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   May Petrochemical Product Production Increases </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    May Petrochemical Product Production Increases </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   942A0352A Tokyo NIKKEI SANGYO SHIMBUN in Japanese 17 Jun 94 
p 13--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> 942A0352A </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIKKEI SANGYO SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
CSO 

  [Text] According to performance such as major petrochemical 
product production in May announced on 16 June by the 
Petrochemical Industry Association (Chairman Hajime Murata), 
production of the four major resins such as polyethylene each 
increased compared to the same month of the previous year. The 
increase rate, starting with high-density polyethylene (HDPE) 
which was 8 percent, was 6 percent for both low-density 
polyethylene (LDPE) and polystyrene (PS), and 3 percent for 
polypropylene (PP). The four resins all have exceeded the same 
month of the previous year since November 1991. 
  Production increased "because previously sluggish domestic 
demand recovered" (Petrochemical Industry Association). Viewing 
domestic shipment amounts, LDPE and HDPE each were the same as 
the same month of the previous year; PP increased 2 percent and 
PS increased 1 percent. That for electrical machinery, VTR's 
[video tape recorders], and others slumped, but that for 
television and air conditioners increased. In addition, that for 
wrapping material and sundries also increased. 
  In exports, on the other hand, PS for Southeast Asia was 
favorable, but overall it leveled off, affected by the high yen. 
As a result, the total amount of shipments was at about the same 
level as the previous year for the four resins. Inventory is 
piling, up with regularly scheduled repairs to production 
facilities drawing close. 
  Production of ethylene, which is the basic raw material of 
petrochemicals, was 519,700 tons, an increase of 6 percent 
compared to the same month of the previous year. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

