<F P=100> HUNGARY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Party Leaders React to MSZP Election Victory </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Party Leaders React to MSZP Election Victory </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Goncz on Convening National Assembly </H4>

<F P=102> LD2905205194 Budapest Duna TV in Hungarian 1945 GMT 29 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2905205194 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest Duna TV </F>
<F P=105>  Hungarian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with President Arpad Goncz by unidentified </F>
reporter at the Duna Palace in Budapest -- live] 
  [Excerpt] [Reporter] As president of the Republic, what do 
you consider to be the next important thing from the country's 
point of view, the thing which you advise to the country? 
  [Goncz] That the country should have a stable and acceptable 
government. 
  [Reporter] The people have expressed their view quite 
radically and -- in both rounds of the elections -- quite 
massively, in terms of turnout. 
  [Goncz] The people deserve respect and honor for this. 
  [Reporter] However, after this, should the parties not be 
expected to effect the transition in a similarly radical and 
speedily manner? Will you ask the party leaders tomorrow to do 
this? 
  [Goncz] That goes without saying. The campaign, the election 
is over, now all parties must bear in mind the welfare of the 
country. 
  [Reporter] When do you plan to convene the National 
Assembly? 
  [Goncz] The National Assembly must be convened within 30 
days 
of the announcement of the election result, but I sincerely hope 
that I will be able to convene it as soon as possible. I cannot 
give a date. 
  [Reporter] Mr. President, when can peace and calm be 
expected 
to prevail in the country again? 
  [Goncz] I do not feel that the country is in a state of war. 
I could hardly have conceived a more peaceful election. So, I 
believe that the state of calm will be reestablished soon -- the 
campaign is over. As to when the nation's peace of mind is to 
prevail, let me say that it will occur if the nation can draw a 
final account of all the phases of its history prior to 1918 and 
close that account. However, it might take a generation. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

