<F P=100> HUNGARY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Party Leaders React to MSZP Election Victory </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Party Leaders React to MSZP Election Victory </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    SZDSZ's Petoe on Need for `Compromise' </H4>

<F P=102> LD3005174094 Budapest Kossuth Radio Network in Hungarian 
1600 GMT 30 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD3005174094 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest Kossuth Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Hungarian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] After the results of the second round of the 
parliamentary elections, the Alliance of Free Democrats [SZDSZ] 
is forced to give up the possibility of recommending a nominee 
for the post of prime minister to the MSZP [Hungarian Socialist 
Party], which finished first in the election. This was 
discussed, among other things, at the SZDSZ press briefing. 
Judit Laszlo reports from there. 
  [Laszlo] [passage omitted] Considering the chances for a 
coalition, party Chairman Ivan Petoe said that the SZDSZ did not 
view the distribution of ministries purely as a mathematical 
exercise. Were the MSZP-SZDSZ coalition to come into being, it 
would be the result of a historic compromise, Petoe said. 
[passage omitted] 
  The price of the compromise is that the would-be coalition 
should implement a liberal economic program but the SZDSZ would 
like to see the personnel guarantees for this too, Petoe said. 
He also stressed that the SZDSZ would be able to conduct 
coalition negotiations only with a united MSZP, because the 
SZDSZ does not wish to set itself up as a judge to decide over 
the issues of dispute that exist between the various wings of 
the MSZP. 
  An MSZP-SZDSZ coalition is inconceivable unless a compromise 
solution is arrived at in respect of the person of the prime 
minister. At the same time, the SZDSZ is not in a position to 
make recommendations for the person of the prime minister, it 
was said at the press briefing. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

