<F P=100> HUNGARY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Party Leaders React to MSZP Election Victory </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Party Leaders React to MSZP Election Victory </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Goncz on Parties' `Moral Obligations' </H4>

<F P=102> LD3005215094 Budapest MTV Television Network in Hungarian 
1730 GMT 30 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD3005215094 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest MTV Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Hungarian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] Hungarian President Arpad Goncz received the 
leading representatives of the parties in the parliament 
building earlier today. 
  [Begin Goncz recording] [passage omitted] If I myself had to 
define what the electorate voted for or against I would say that 
the country had two desires. One of these is that the country 
itself should not break into two societies -- with a society of 
the poor people on the one hand and a society of those amassing 
immeasurable riches for themselves on the other. Parallel with 
this -- obviously not consciously -- is that we should not break 
into two parts, east and west Hungary. 
  As a result of the election the parties have several moral 
obligations. First, they should focus their energies to achieve 
an economic revival as much as possible and in accordance with a 
thorough plan. Neither the government nor parliament can 
fulfill this task on its own. In the interest of a common 
objective, a national consensus must be established -- as wide 
as possible -- for the fulfillment of this goal. In other 
words, in my judgment efforts should be made for establishing a 
coalition government, but naturally I cannot interfere in this, 
nor do I want to. [passage omitted] 
  I must add that I am convinced that the electorate of the 
country has helped bring to victory a future modern and European 
social democratic party. [passage omitted] [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

