<F P=100> CZECH REPUBLIC </F>
<H3> <TI>   Experts: Former USSR Greatest Security Threat </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Experts: Former USSR Greatest Security Threat </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2905193594 Prague MLADA FRONTA DNES in Czech 23 May 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> AU2905193594 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague MLADA FRONTA DNES </F>
<F P=105>  Czech </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["km"-signed report: "Experts See a Greater Risk in the </F>
Former USSR Than in Bosnia"] 
  [Text] If there is any external threat to the Czech 
Republic, then it is, above all, the developments in the former 
Soviet Union. The International Relations Institute experts, who 
prepared the documentation for the government concept of 
security policy, believe that even the present conflict in 
former Yugoslavia is less dangerous for the Czech Republic than 
the ethnic, political, and economic conflicts in the post-Soviet 
countries. 
  According to the document, which the government experts used 
when drafting the security concept, the most perilous disputes 
in Europe are the Polish-Russian, possibly Polish-Ukrainian, 
Polish- Lithuanian, and Russian-Baltic conflicts. 
  In the context of the war in former Yugoslavia, the Czech 
experts point out particularly the possibility of the 
penetration of militant Islamic fundamentalism into Europe. 
Another security hazard in Central Europe could be the 
nationalist attempts at revision of the borders and the 
so-called disputable territory -- Greater Germany, Greater 
Hungary. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-30761 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu104_c_94009" </HT>


<HEADER>
