<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN Asked To Discuss `Occupied Territories' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UN Asked To Discuss `Occupied Territories' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2705233894 Zagreb Radio Croatia Network in Serbo-Croatian 
2200 GMT 27 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2705233894 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb Radio Croatia Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Republic of Croatia has requested that the 
situation in the occupied territories of the Republic of Croatia 
be added to the agenda of the 49th session of the UN General 
Assembly on 13 September. This was disclosed by the Croatian 
permanent mission at the UN, which has submitted a formal 
request to this effect to UN Secretary General Butrus 
Butrus-Ghali. The text of the request stresses that the efforts 
made by international mediators have so far produced no results 
that could be described as significant progress in implementing 
UN Security Council resolutions. By signing the Zagreb 
agreement Croatia has shown its readiness to resolve the problem 
of its occupied areas peacefully. But the Serb side -- by 
refusing to resume the talks -- is showing that it is not 
willing to accept the UN Security Council resolutions, while the 
Federal Republic of Yugoslavia is continuing and speeding up the 
silent integration of these areas into its state system, the 
official request by the Croatian mission says. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-30767 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu104_k_94003" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-104 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  27 May 1994 </DATE1>

