<F P=100> SLOVAKIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Agreement With Russian Interior Ministry Signed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Agreement With Russian Interior Ministry Signed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2905204594 Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 1630 GMT 29 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2905204594 </F>
<F P=104>  Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 1630 GMT 29 May 94 </F>

<F P=105> Slovak </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] A cooperation agreement between the Interior 
Ministries of the Russian Federation and the Slovak Republic was 
signed in Moscow today by Ministers Viktor Yerin and Ladislav 
Pittner. [passage omitted] 
  Our correspondent Jan Smihula interviewed Ladislav Pittner 
shortly before the minister's departure from the Russian 
capital. [passage omitted] 
  [Begin recording] [Smihula] Mr. Minister, your talks with 
your Russian counterpart lasted 30 minutes longer than 
originally planned. Does this mean that some disagreements, 
problems have emerged? How do you assess today's talks? 
  [Pittner] Our talks lasted longer not because of 
disagreements, but because of discussing further spheres of 
cooperation on which agreements are being drafted by our experts 
for signing. Above all, this concerns the issue of police 
attaches who are to work in our two countries. A Russian police 
attache based in Bratislava will probably be accredited to also 
work in other countries of Central and Eastern Europe. 
Regarding our police attache, I was promised that he will be 
given opportunities to widen his activities to reach other 
former Soviet republics. 
  The other issue concerned archives and we received full 
support from the minister for gaining access to the archives to 
see, for instance, files on people taken against their will to 
Russia. [passage omitted] 
  We were also promised help in searching for one part of the 
President Jozef Tiso [World War II pro-Nazi leader] archive. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

