<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN Says Muslim Offensives Triggering Clashes </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UN Says Muslim Offensives Triggering Clashes </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2705235894 Belgrade TANJUG in English 2234 GMT 27 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2705235894 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool item"] </F>
  [Text] New York, May 27 (TANJUG) -- Bosnian Moslem 
offensive operations in central and northern Bosnia have 
triggered clashes with the Serbs in the areas of Maglaj, Olovo 
and Gradacac, U.N. spokesman for peacekeeping operations Fred 
Eckhard said at a regular press briefing on Friday. 
  There is fighting also around Bihac in the west, where Serb 
forces are supposed to be attacking, Eckhard went on to say. 
  He explained that talks were still in progress on the 
withdrawal of Bosnian Serbs from the exclusion zone around 
Gorazde in the southeast, but so far without any concrete 
results. He noted there was no deadline or ultimatum for the 
withdrawal. 
  Earlier this year, Moslem forces had mounted a strong 
offensive from Gorazde, which should have been demilitarized a 
year ago together with five other U.N.-designated safe areas in 
Bosnia. When the offensive was on the verge of collapse, the 
international community stepped in and ordered air strikes 
against the Serbs. 
  Bosnian Moslem ambassador to the United Nations Muhamed 
Sacirbej has written to the U.N. Security Council, accusing 
Secretary-General Butrus Butrus-Ghali of putting an equation 
mark between the Bosnian Moslems and Serbs. 
  Sacirbej took exception to Butrus-Ghali's blaming both the 
Serbs and the Moslems for failing to honour their undertakings 
in connection with the safe area of Gorazde, and called for 
bombing the Serbs who he said understand only the language of 
threats and force. 
  Sacirbej explained that the cease-fire agreement for 
Gorazde, 
reached in Belgrade in mid-April by Bosnian Serb President 
Radovan Karadzic and the U.N. secretary-general's special envoy 
Yasushi Akashi, was not binding on the Moslem side which had not 
taken part in the talks. 

</TEXT>

