<F P=101> Kosovo </F>
<H3> <TI>   Members of Illegal `Chamber of Commerce' Arrested </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Members of Illegal `Chamber of Commerce' Arrested </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2805173194 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1518 GMT 28 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2805173194 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Pristina, 28 May (TANJUG) -- The Serbian Internal 
Affairs Ministry has detained representatives of the "Kosovo 
Illegal Chamber of Commerce" who unlawfully tried to set up a 
"Kosovo Chamber of Commerce." 
  As a meeting of the "executive committee" of this illegal 
organization was due to start the police stormed the premises, 
prevented the meeting from taking place and arrested Ismailj 
Kastrati and Sulejman Ahmetaj, the "president" and "secretary" 
of this Albanian "chamber", together with 11 "committee" 
members. The first two were detained while the others were 
released after interrogation. 
  Reporting on this incident, the newspaper BUJKU said that 
the 
police acted correctly. The paper also recalls the statements 
by Serbian officials saying they will not tolerate any 
organization of parallel power in Kosmet. 
  BUJKU admits that the Serbian authorities granted licenses 
to 
14,000 private enterprises whose owners were mostly ethnic 
Albanians, but they cannot accept their being organized outside 
official institutions. 
  The Chamber of Commerce of Kosovo and Metohija does exist in 
Pristina. It represents the interests of all economic subjects 
regardless of their nationality. Ethnic Albanians are also 
members, and some of their private entrepreneurs are even using 
the premises that they leased from the Chamber. 
  However, the political group rallied round Ibrahim Rugova is 
trying to establish the parallel forms of power and thus prove 
that Kosovo is outside Serbia and that it is allegedly "a 
separate independent state." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

