<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Churkin Meets With Leaders in Zagreb </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Churkin Meets With Leaders in Zagreb </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD3005181194 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1751 GMT 30 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD3005181194 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, May 30 (TANJUG) -- Russia's special envoy 
and Deputy Foreign Minister Vitaliy Churkin is in Zagreb at the 
start of a new mission aimed at settling the conflict in former 
Yugoslavia. As announced in Moscow, Churkin is to meet with 
members of the Croatian leadership in Zagreb on Monday to 
discuss the implementation of a Russia-brokered agreement on a 
cessation of hostilities between Croatia and the Republic of 
Serb Krajina. They are also expected to discuss the situation 
in war-torn Bosnia-Herzegovina and other issues regarding the 
settling of the conflict in former Yugoslavia. 
  On Tuesday, Churkin is expected to leave for Belgrade, where 
he will meet with Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic to 
discuss the finding of a settlement for the Bosnian conflict. 
  Churkin is in Zagreb and Belgrade on the eve of a meeting 
scheduled for June 2-3 by U.N. special envoy for former 
Yugoslavia Yasushi Akashi. The Russian envoy wants to check 
once again Belgrade's and Zagreb's stands on the Bosnian crisis. 
Over the past few days Churkin has on several occasions 
criticized the Bosnian Moslems for their attacks on Serb 
positions in Bosnia. 
  A ranking official at the Russian Foreign Ministry told the 
Russian Interfax agency on Monday that special importance was 
being attached to Churkin's current mission because it comes 
after the failure of the meeting between the international 
"contact group" for Bosnia-Herzegovina and the representatives 
of Bosnia's three warring sides. 
  The official said the declaration released at the Geneva 
meeting of the foreign ministers of the European Union, the 
United States and Russia on the territorial division of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina according to which the Bosnian Serbs should 
get 49 per cent and the Croat-Moslem federation 51 per cent of 
the territory of that former Yugoslav republic -- was still 
effective. 
  Russian sources claim that such a proportion will most 
probably be accepted both by the Croat and the Moslem side, but 
the main problem will be the "quality" of the territories. 
  The Serbs, who are now holding 70 per cent of the territory 
of Bosnia-Herzegovina, are willing to give up a certain 
percentage provided that they do not lose anything of "quality". 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-30827 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu104_d_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-104 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  29 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> SLOVAKIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ethnic Hungarian Groups Want Closer Union </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ethnic Hungarian Groups Want Closer Union </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2905123094 Budapest Kossuth Radio Network in Hungarian 
1000 GMT 29 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2905123094 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest Kossuth Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Hungarian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The political movements of the Hungarian community 
in Slovakia, after many earlier conflicts and disputes, are, 
according to the signs, striving for more intensive cooperation. 
Ildiko Nagy reports from Bratislava. 
  [Nagy] At its session yesterday, the National Council of 
Coexistence authorized the movement's executive body to begin 
discussions, with the involvement of the Hungarian Christian 
Democratic Movement [MKDH] and the Hungarian Civic Party [MOS], 
about setting up a close triple coalition. 
  Although the delegates took tacit cognizance of the fact 
that 
discussions are to be pursued with the MKDH, the current 
coalition partner, they are of the view that the close unity of 
Slovakia's Hungarian community will in future be rendered 
possible by their union. However, on account of the criticisms 
connected with it, they are presuming that it cannot be 
developed at the moment, and that is why discussions have to be 
started about the establishment of a triple coalition. 
  According to Coexistence, the two partners -- that is the 
MKDH and the MOS -- must undertake a commitment to form a joint 
deputies' group in parliament, to put forward a joint candidate 
for the local government elections in October, to create a joint 
local-government and foreign affairs council, and in the future 
to take a united stand on forums abroad. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

