<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Churkin on Efforts to Resolve Deadlock </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Churkin on Efforts to Resolve Deadlock </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD3105222394 Zagreb HTV Television in Serbo-Croatian 2125 
GMT 31 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD3105222394 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb HTV Television </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Passages within quotation marks are recorded] </F>
  [Text] After the talks with President Tudjman in Zagreb 
this afternoon, Russian special envoy Vitaliy Churkin looked 
more than satisfied when he met reporters. According to him, 
important agreements have been reached. 
  [Churkin, in English with superimposed Serbo-Croatian 
translation] "I had two main tasks today. First, to make sure 
that all sides are ready for the very important meeting in 
Geneva on Thursday. Second, I was trying to find a way out of 
the deadlock in the talks on economic cooperation between Zagreb 
and Knin." 
  [Announcer] Churkin expects that all negotiating parties 
will 
turn up in Geneva, for -- as he puts it -- the negotiators have 
an obligation to the world community. 
  [Churkin] "On the second subject, I have an impression that 
the deadlock in the economic talks has been resolved. I am 
encouraged that we will soon see the beginning of the talks on 
economic cooperation, which will immediately come up with 
concrete economic measures, which will in turn enable further 
important steps to normalize relations between Zagreb and Knin." 
  [Announcer] Although Churkin announced further talks, the 
question of the venue and the date for the talks still remains 
open. 
  [Churkin] "I am not in a position at this point to make an 
announcement, but I believe that a venue will be found to their 
mutual satisfaction. As I said, the most important thing is 
that the deadlock has been resolved." 
  [Announcer] Churkin expects a great deal from the Geneva 
talks. He believes that the world community is at this point 
offering the greatest chances for peace, and it is up to the 
negotiators to accept it. To use his full influence on all 
parties in the Geneva negotiations, he is to travel to Sarajevo 
tomorrow for talks with Alija Izetbegovic and Kresimir Zubak. 

</TEXT>

