<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Serbs Arrest Six for Suspected Arms Smuggling </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Serbs Arrest Six for Suspected Arms Smuggling </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0106100194 Belgrade Radio Beograd Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 0900 GMT 1 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU0106100194 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade Radio Beograd Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] During a routine check of a UN Protection Forces 
[UNPROFOR] vehicle at the Kasindol Street checkpoint, civilian 
and military police of the Serbian Republic discovered a group 
of people that are strongly suspected of smuggling on behalf of 
the current authorities in Sarajevo. 
  Among the detainees is also an UNPROFOR member. The 
detainees were carrying a large amount of foreign currency, and 
it has been established that the suspects were charged with 
purchasing equipment for the army and the police of the former 
Bosnia-Herzegovina and that they had set off for the airport 
with this intention, from where they were supposed to fly to 
Zagreb. As the incumbent offices have reported, six people have 
been arrested and detained in prison, among them (Angelo 
Andrea), an Italian citizen who was in charge of the liaison 
with correspondents in the UNPROFOR civilian sector. 
  The search has established that Savcinovic, Cakovic, and 
Kujic all possessed UN press cards, while, as he claims, he had 
the card of the UN High Commissioner for Refugees from the 
Muslim government because he was in charge of control of 
humanitarian cargo in Frankfurt. [sentence as heard] A letter 
was also found on Halilovic, which claims that Operation 
Parachute will be stopped in a month. An investigation is under 
way. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

