<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bosnian Croats To Use Kuna as Currency </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Bosnian Croats To Use Kuna as Currency </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD3105184994 Zagreb HTV Television in Serbo-Croatian 1730 
GMT 31 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD3105184994 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb HTV Television </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Croatian dinar together with the German mark has 
today remained a means of payment in Herceg-Bosna. The kuna and 
the [smaller denomination] lipa have not yet arrived in the 
markets and shops. However, the withdrawal of the Croatian 
dinar from circulation has started at the financial transactions 
bureau. All those with accounts with the bureau are paying 
their last deposits in Croatian dinars and are drawing cash in 
kunas. This is why it is so busy at the bureau's main Mostar 
branch. 
  While citizens are curiously comparing the new currency note 
with that of the German mark, and some even with the old kuna, 
it has to be said that from tomorrow they will be able to change 
dinars for kunas in business banks. The exchange will be 
possible until 5 June and the Croatian dinar will finally be 
withdrawn from circulation on 30 June, according to the 
Herceg-Bosna government's decision. Also according to the 
government's decision, the German mark and the U.S. dollar will 
be official means of payment, together with the kuna. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

