<F P=100> CZECH REPUBLIC </F>
<H3> <TI>   Klaus Discusses Russian Repayment of Debts </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Klaus Discusses Russian Repayment of Debts </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD3105183694 Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network in Czech 1615 
GMT 31 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD3105183694 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Czech </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Prime Minister Vaclav Klaus by station </F>
editor David Stahlavsky; place and date not given -- live or 
recorded] 
  [Excerpts] [Stahlavsky] [passage omitted] Regarding our 
relations with Russia. You have met Andrey Vavilov, first deputy 
finance minister of the Russian Federation. How happy are you 
with the attitude of our former big brother to the debt owed to 
our small country, particularly as this debt is not negligible, 
if we take into consideration the size of our country. Is there 
not a danger that by having our debt repaid we will get 
ourselves into a new form of dependence on Russia? 
  [Klaus] Somebody keeps going on about this. I must be really 
arrogant, as everybody says, because since 15 May I have 
repeatedly said that any sort of dependence on Russia is 
completely out of the question. No one would dream of it. I do 
not know where this idea has come from. We are simply trying to 
get something back for our debts; this is our only aim. We have 
no other conditions and Russia does not attach any. I think 
this is really a fabrication by some politicians, perhaps Mr. 
Daniel Kroupa or someone. [passage omitted] 
  Russia has enormous debts, and not only to us. Its total 
debt is a hundred times bigger than what it owes to the Czech 
Republic. It must repay it at some point. We cannot have any 
illusions that Russia would repay us earlier than the rest of 
the world -- we are not the center of the world. [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

