<F P=106> [MTI report: "Duray for Minority Rights"] </F>
  [Text] Miklos Duray, chairman of the Coexistence Movement, 
only considers the current form of the European stability 
agreement acceptable if certain national minority interests can 
be included in it. In an interview to the [Bratislava] UJ SZO 
on 25 May, Duray said: "Through its legitimate representatives, 
the Hungarian community wishes to participate in drawing up the 
agreement. We reject all such steps that would exclude our 
direct participation.... There are two alternatives. One is 
that we become part of bilateral talks and, in this case, 
naturally, we accept the mediating role of a third party. As a 
second solution, we consider it more important and necessary to 
create a system of agreements within the given country, in our 
case between the Hungarian minority and the government," Duray 
said. 

</TEXT>

