<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Zubak Elected President of Federation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Zubak Elected President of Federation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD3105153394 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1410 GMT 31 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD3105153394 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, May 31 (TANJUG) -- The constituent 
assembly of the Muslim-Croat federation on Tuesday [31 May] 
elected Kresimir Zubak, a Croat, the federation's first 
president, Muslim-controlled Radio Sarajevo reported. At a 
session in Sarajevo which opened on Monday, Ejup Ganic, a 
Muslim, was elected vice-president of the federation. 
  As announced, they will hold the offices during the 
six-month 
period of transition, till the elections. Previously, the 
deputies adopted (with one abstention by a Croat representative) 
an amendment of the constitution of the former Yugoslav Republic 
of Bosnia-Herzegovina and adopted the constitution of the future 
Muslim-Croat federation. 
  The agreement on the setting up of a Muslim-Croat federation 
in Bosnia-Herzegovina was signed in Washington on March 18, 
under strong pressure from the U.S. Representatives of Bosnian 
Serbs were not invited to these talks. Under the Washington 
agreement, the federation would subsequently enter into a 
confederation with neighbouring Croatia. At a recent 
ministerial meeting of the U.S., Russia and the European Union, 
it was agreed that the Muslim-Croat federation get 51 percent, 
and the Serb state 49 percent of Bosnia-Herzegovina. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

