<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Federal </F>
<H3> <TI>   FRY Excluded From Nonaligned Conference </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    FRY Excluded From Nonaligned Conference </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD3105091194 Belgrade TANJUG in English 0825 GMT 31 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD3105091194 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, May 31 (TANJUG) -- A nonaligned ministerial 
conference will open in Cairo on Tuesday and for the first time 
since the foundation of the [Nonaligned] Movement [NAM] it will 
not be attended by officials from Yugoslavia, one of its 
founders and the host of its first summit. This is the result 
of an arbitrary behaviour of the host of the conference, Egypt, 
whose Foreign Minister 'Amr Musa had decided "not to allow 
Serbia" to participate in the meeting for two reasons: because 
he does not recognize the right of the Federal Republic of 
Yugoslavia to succession and because of what he described as 
"Belgrade's involvement in Bosnia and Croatia." 
  Instead of the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia, Egypt invited 
to the conference Moslem officials from the former Yugoslav 
republic of Bosnia-Herzegovina, as well as those from Croatia 
and Slovenia. Officials from Greece, Bulgaria and many 
countries of the former Soviet Union and some West European 
countries will be present as guests or observers. The agenda of 
the conference, to be opened by Egyptian President Husni 
Mubarak, will include the crisis in Bosnia-Herzegovina, the 
conflicts in Rwanda, Cambodia and Yemen, the Movement's future 
in the light of the new world order and economic problems of the 
member-countries. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

