<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chile's Pinochet Arrives on Unofficial Visit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Chile's Pinochet Arrives on Unofficial Visit </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Dlouhy on Possible Arms Purchases </H4>

<F P=102> AU3005083594 Prague CTK in English 1816 GMT 29 May 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU3005083594 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prague, May 29 (CTK) -- Industry and Trade Minister 
Vladimir Dlouhy today told CTK that Chilean General Augusto 
Pinochet was considered in his country a "standard 
representative of certain circles" and if he came to the Czech 
Republic to negotiate trade deals he would not to take a stand 
on his visit. "That is the prerogative of other bodies in this 
country," Dlouhy said. 
  He emphasized that he had neither been briefed on Pinochet's 
visit beforehand nor asked to meet or negotiate with him. He 
said, however, he did not rule out the possibility of his 
ministry, as the license administration, being asked to agree to 
arms exports -- but to Chile, not General Pinochet, he stressed. 
  If Pinochet concluded the deals planned, according to valid 
Czech law the ministry would certainly take a position on it, 
Dlouhy said, adding that the ministry's position would not be 
absolutely dependent on whether it was Pinochet or someone else 
who negotiated the deals. 
  What is important is not that it is Pinochet who is leading 
the Chilean delegation but that the delegation will come to buy 
Czech weapons, Dlouhy said. If Pinochet comes as an official 
representative of the Chilean Armed Forces then some contract 
would probably be agreed upon and the possible exports of 
armaments would have to be approved by the license 
administration, Dlouhy said. 
  Consideration will be given to whether Chile is among 
countries to which the Czech Republic wants to limit arms 
exports to or not. "Chile is today a democratic country and I 
would therefore expect that the stand would be positive if the 
final user of weapons is clear. But I cannot say beforehand," 
he added. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

