<H3> <TI>   Klaus on `Absurd' EU Accusation on Dumping </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Klaus on `Absurd' EU Accusation on Dumping </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2605081294 Prague CTK in English 0641 GMT 26 May 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2605081294 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prague, May 26 (CTK) -- Price dumping is 
unacceptable to the Czech Government, and to accuse the Czech 
Republic of such a thing is absurd, Prime Minister Vaclav Klaus 
said after yesterday's cabinet meeting, in connection with the 
anti-dumping procedures initiated by the European Union against 
nine Czech cement producers. The whole affair is an example of 
what is bad in trade relations between the European Union and 
the Czech Republic, Klaus said. 
  Trade barriers are a problem for the Czech Republic, which 
would welcome the abolition of duties before 2001, the deadline 
set by the association agreement, he continued. The 
anti-dumping procedures were initiated on March 28 against 
Slovak and Polish as well as Czech producers. The European 
Commission, at the request of the German Association of Cement 
Producers, opened an investigation similar to a trial, in which 
the accused are represented by lawyers. 

</TEXT>

