<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Approves Bills on Security Service </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Approves Bills on Security Service </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2605081694 Prague CTK in English 1841 GMT 25 May 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2605081694 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prague, May 25 (CTK) -- At its meeting today, the 
Czech Government approved a bill on the Czech security services 
and a bill on the activity of the Security and Information 
Service (BIS) and on the position and obligations of its 
members. Both bills were drafted on the basis of the principles 
which were thoroughly discussed by parliament. 
  Premier Vaclav Klaus told journalists after the meeting that 
the bill on security services defines the basic framework of 
their activity and basic forms of coordination between them and 
additionally states the way the services are to be made 
accountable. In this sense it is an umbrella law of global 
nature and serves as a basis for another law on the BIS, Klaus 
said. 
  He confirmed that the government had agreed with a proposal 
by its Legislative Council that BIS installations are guarded by 
policemen and not by counter-intelligence members. 
  Klaus described as a considerable positive shift the fact 
that, apart from general control, the new law would make 
security services less accountable to parliament and more to the 
government. To entrust a security service with a task was 
basically a matter of the government and president, with the 
president entrusting security services with tasks through the 
government, Klaus said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

