<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   ODS Supports Screening, Checking Violations </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    ODS Supports Screening, Checking Violations </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2605193594 Prague CTK in English 1746 GMT 26 May 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2605193594 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prague, May 26 (CTK) -- The main government 
coalition party, the Civic Democratic Party (ODS), supports the 
strict application of the lustration law and believes that any 
doubts about its violation should be checked, ODS Deputy 
Chairman Jiri Vlach said at a press conference today. 
  He was reacting to claims that the lustration (screening) 
law 
had been violated in the case of two high-ranking officers of 
the Czech Army. The allegation was made by an ODS member of 
parliament Tomas Fejfar, deputy chairman of the Parliamentary 
Defense and Security Committee on the Nova television station on 
May 24. He said Defense Minister Antonin Baudys had admitted 
the fact to him. 
  The newspaper RUDE PRAVO then speculated the following day 
the men in question were Karel Pezl, former Czech Army chief of 
staff and now military adviser to Baudys, and Colonel Rostislav 
Kotil who commands the South Sector of the UNPROFOR [United 
Nations Protection Force] peace keeping unit in Croatia. 
  Vlach said today that Fejfar's claims should be properly 
investigated. 
  Baudys told reporters today that both Pezl and Kotil met all 
the requirements of the lustration law as stipulated in Interior 
Ministry documents. 
  Under the Lustration Law of October 1991 persons who held 
senior posts in the Communist Party, the paramilitary militia or 
the StB [State Security] secret police in the former regime are 
debarred from holding state functions for five years. 
  Colonel Kotil told CTK today that he was considering suing 
those who reported he had received a positive lustration 
certificate (proving his collaboration). 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

