<F P=100> THE FORMER YUGOSLAV REPUBLIC OF MACEDONIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Berlusconi Offered Help Against Greek Embargo </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Berlusconi Offered Help Against Greek Embargo </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2705204394 Skopje MIC in English 27 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2705204394 </F>
<F P=104>  Skopje MIC </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Italy in Support of Macedonia"] </F>
  [Text] "The Prime Minister of Italy Silvio Berlusconi feels 
that the Greek embargo against Macedonia [The Former Yugoslav 
Republic of Macedonia -- FYROM] is irrational and that, as a man 
who puts the economy in the forefront, he can simply not accept 
this as a form of communication with another country," 
Macedonia's Prime Minister Branko Crvenkovski emphasized at 
yesterday's press conference, following his visit to Italy. 
Crvenkovski emphasized that Berlusconi had promised that at the 
next EU meeting on Corfu, he would express the Italian stance in 
relation to the Greek embargo, in front of the Greek government 
representatives. 
  The Macedonian Prime Minister expressed satisfaction with 
what Macedonia displayed on a cultural plan within the framework 
of the manifestation "Macedonia in the Honor of St. Cyril," but 
also on a political plan, after the realized contacts with the 
high-ranking officials of Italy and Vatican. 
  Branko Crvenkovski underlined that a particular emphasis in 
the talks was placed on Italy's economic participation in 
Macedonian and the East-West project, which, together with its 
sub-projects, such as the gas line and the traffic route, offers 
possibilities for a joint appearance of construction workers 
from both countries on the Albanian market. 

</TEXT>

